Here are some of the conclusions of the latest survey of Latinobarómetro conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, allows to track changes in attitudes in the region.
The results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October, there are two issues.
The first is relatively lively mood prevailing in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes toward democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in many countries of the Pacific coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% annually since 2002, support for democracy has risen from 40% in 2005 reduced to 61% this year.
Also expanded in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a big drop in production last year.
However, only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents in the region were satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in his country, the same number as last year but considerably higher than 25% in 2001 (Chart 3).
About 34% said they trusted the U.S. Congress and 45% in its government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but significantly higher than in 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, the economic turmoil in Latin America seriously affected the support for democracy.
The fact that is sustained for the global financial crisis is probably due to many Latin American countries were affected only by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
Furthermore, the existence of a social safety net stronger has helped to protect the poor.
(The Economic Commission for Latin America United Nations reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only marginally in 2009 and has fallen again this year, up 32%.)
However, the mood varies greatly from one country to another (see Figure 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
That sentiment is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and violent crime have increased.
For the second time since the survey began, more respondents mentioned crime in Latin America, rather than unemployment as the most serious problem facing their country (see Chart 5).
About 31% say either they or a close relative, a victim of crime in the past year, a figure that has fallen from 38% last year and is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
More positive economic returns are reflected in increased support for private enterprise and market economy: around 71% of respondents in the region say that private companies are essential for development, while in 2007 it was only the 56% (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, compared with 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% support to private companies), although its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriated many private companies.
Brazil is the country that has a greater leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, same number as last year) and Venezuela (9% versus 11% a year).
However, U.S. is the country considered most influential by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela has that title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
