China keeps its bid to reduce between 40 and 45 percent their emissions of greenhouse gases by 2020, said Su Wei, a representative of that country at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16 Conference of the Parties to the Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said that his country has made tremendous efforts to reduce carbon footprint and to retrofit their industry.
In fact, he explained, in the last four years the country has invested $ 245 million in efforts to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases.
However he made clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue working with the international community in this area.
He said that China's strategy on climate change is divided into four areas: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programs.
In all of these items have made progress, including the adoption last year of a new Energy Act, which sets out the objectives stated in terms of reducing emissions, he said.
On the other hand, said that in China, federal authorities have been working collaboratively with state and local, to achieve the objectives of energy saving, efficient energy use and emissions.
Moreover, he added, are underway or already completed several multi-year plans, both funded by the Chinese government, as governments of other countries.
