Climate: the bungling of France in their promises of funding
A year after the Copenhagen agreement, it is time to consider whether restrictions on funding pledges quickly unlocked (called fast start or early) made by developed countries.
And they have revealed the bungling French.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries pledged to provide U.S. $ 30,000 million between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged 7,200 million euros in three years and France EUR 1,260 million (ie, 420 million per year).
During the opening of the COP16, the EU has put on the table their best cards to convince their partners that their commitment to financing fast start is true: a report detailing the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a major side event, the distribution of leaflets ...
Transparent operation and significant result was appreciated for what really matters: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries do the same and the same level of accuracy.
The EU announced that it has released 2010 2.200 million, which puts it on track towards meeting its commitment of 7,200 million in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that additional efforts are made without prejudice to the ODA.
Unfortunately, there has been no agreement on what "new and additional.
When the European Commission proposed a harmonization, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Currently, each choosing the most convenient reference.
For example, the European Commission has taken as the base year 2009: maintaining international funding and added 150 million over three years in funding fast start.
Other countries have chosen similar references in regard to year or at the level of official development assistance.
By contrast, France considers that funding for "all new projects" of 2010 are "new and additional."
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' expenditures and the overall level of official development aid.
Specifically, the total amount of French aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while pretending to respect their commitments with regard to fund "new and additional" ...
Another crucial element, the breakdown between grants and loans.
Once again, there is no standard and each choosing the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that every dollar borrowed donated equals one euro.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to reducing emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that donate ... At best, only should be computed for the cost of their loan commitments to the country granting the loan (ie, equivalent to an interest rate).
But France is not useful such reasoning: "respect" its commitment of 420 million euros by 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of gifts (36.1 million euros); see the EU to see with his own eyes.
It is the only EU country that uses so often the loan.
Germany is used by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments to 100% of donations.
In other words, when most of the European Union provides a euro to fulfill its commitment, France contributes only ten cents and believes that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In summary, in its funding fast start, France is a double abuse: first, in relation to actions in time and, secondly, in relation to the actual financial outlay.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, manages to give the impression that spends 420 million "new and additional" as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (Bercy think it's because he has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States to continue to donate when they can simply borrow?) As in negotiations, as developing countries are not stupid ...
The chapter on finance is a trifle early, relatively short time, under all the climate negotiations.
But it might be a grain of sand over the vast machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully not.
Whatever, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could herald a change in its method of calculation for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention to respect its commitments and the same way as the other European Union countries.
But, especially, France could make further discussions on the stakes at play in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter is currently under discussion): do not get rid of the issue of "additionality" and the method compute loans.
France could change its position to become so progressive on this issue as it is with others.
Therefore, we can only hope the new Minister of Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who come to Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about the fast start of France and its vision of "additionality" and the use of the loans would improve the confidence level needed to advance international negotiations.
Warning about the pesticides ingested by children
A 10 year old boy eat a day 81 different chemicals, according to a study published on Wednesday Générations Futures Association (the old movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a statistical significant considering the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problems addressed," Oise purchased in supermarkets and Paris between July and September food often consume a boy about ten years in four meals and a snack daily.
These meals taken as a model that follow the official recommendations (five portions of fruit and vegetables, dairy products and three of 1.5 liters of water a day) and sweets, were examined in the laboratory for chemical , pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as carcinogenic insurance, as well as 37 substances which can act as endocrine disrupters (PE), according to research by various institutions such as International Centre for Research on Cancer.
"Although in almost all cases, not exceed the legal limits for each of the individual chemicals, our study clearly shows that exposure of consumers to potentially carcinogenic pollutants and / or PE is worrying," says the association.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk alone contains more than a dozen potential carcinogenic residues and three insurance considered carcinogenic, as well as about twenty residues can disrupt the hormonal system.
Apples, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack for school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, including in food, in which the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the Russian steak, canned tuna and even a loaf of bread or gum were adorned with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, the analysis found the presence of nitrate and chloroform.
At dinner, the slice of salmon was the most "nutritious" chemical residues detected with 34 and even the analysis of the plastic plate used for heating food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk that create these "cocktail of pollutants" consumer "is probably underestimated," says the study.
Ecology European Alliance Les Verts (EE-LV), meanwhile, has proposed "against the seriousness of the situation" a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases of civilization."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EASA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
